{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ffca357e-b23d-47fe-85f6-fe6ab0ed77a1","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` means **one instance per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, **there are no such request boundaries**. The app is one long-running process, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` lives forever, accumulating stale tracked entities.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a fresh `DbContext` per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use a `DbContext` factory** (preferred for more control):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nThe factory approach is generally recommended because it makes the context lifetime explicit and avoids accidental long-lived tracking.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6d272a20-edef-48b3-80e1-4dbb1e4bef0a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — the app is a single long-running process. So `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same `DbContext` instance is reused for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":406,"requestId":"B800:2EAF75:FF9931:1402B99:69FFDA59"},"id":"ce6f5cd9-3166-4af9-ae4d-cef8a6070576","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:07:46.795Z","parentId":"1191ddf7-162e-4dcb-ab6d-152bee7086a9"}
